## 3.2 CRYSTALS-Kyber Key Definitions

## 3.3 NTRU Prime Key Definitions

NTRU Prime’s key generation algorithms are split into two cases: NTRU Prime and NTRU LPRime. They respectively apply a Quotient- and Product-version of NTRU to a prime ring.

### 3.3.1  Secret Key Definitions

From the NTRU Prime specification,  for NTRU Prime Core, we have a parameter space $(p,q,w)$, where $p$, $q$  are prime numbers and $w$ is a positive integer. All are subject to; $2p \geq 3w$, $q \geq 16w + 1$ and $x^p -x -1$ is irreducible in the polynomial ring $(\mathbb{Z}/q)[x]$. 

Keys are then generated as polynomials in the ring $R_q = \mathbb{Z}_q [x]/(x^p - x- 1)$. The NTRU Prime Core secret key contains $f$ and $1/g$ (both polynomials in the ring $R_q$). Streamlined NTRU Prime adds a KEM construction and contains an extra uniform random $\rho$ used for implicit rejection. Optionally $\rho$ could be replaced by an RNG seed (TODO: not sure how to include this, I left it out for now, but probably should be the default option, since $\rho$ includes the encoding). (TODO: should encoding be optional? I don't think so.: Optionally an encoding parameter $t_1$ (default $TRUE$) to apply a deterministic encoding algorithm to all keys/inputs/ciphertexts).

NTRUPrimePrivateKey ::= SEQUENCE {
    version INTEGER,     -- v0
    f  BIT STRING,      -- vector(p)
    g1  BIT STRING,      -- vector(p) (of 1/g)
    r BIT STRING,	-- implicit rejection
}

From the NTRU Prime specification, the Streamlined NTRU LPRime secret key contains vector a

NTRULPRimePrivateKey ::= SEQUENCE {
  version INTEGER,  	-- v0
  a BIT STRING,      -- vector(p)
  t1 [0] IMPLICIT OPTIONAL {
    t1  BOOL, 		-- tighter encoding option
  }
}

